    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2014371937" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2014371937" />
    <a title="Lance" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46538050-lance"><img alt="Lance" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1441159873p2/46538050.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2014371937?book_show_action=true">Jun 04, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lance" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lance" href="/user/show/46538050-lance">Lance</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Lance by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/54304445-baby-adam">Baby Adam</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=2017">2017</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=series">series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46538050-lance?shelf=looking-for-clues">looking-for-clues</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2014371937" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5076778493530069148">&quot;<i>He had never before been quite so acutely aware for the particular quality and function of November, its ripeness and hushed sadness.</i>&quot;<br/><br/>I know, why does the Cadfael series have to end, with so many medieval mysteries that could yet be solved?<br/><br/>&quot;<i>He painted a battle that could neither be won by either party nor lost by either</i>&quot;<br/><br/>No series can go on forever, but it&apos;s hard to say goodbye to old friends made through the course of 21 books, 21 mysteries solved together.<br/><br/>&quot;<i>There was no other way but straight f</i></span>
  <span id="freeText5076778493530069148" style="display:none">"<i>He had never before been quite so acutely aware for the particular quality and function of November, its ripeness and hushed sadness.</i>"<br /><br />I know, why does the Cadfael series have to end, with so many medieval mysteries that could yet be solved?<br /><br />"<i>He painted a battle that could neither be won by either party nor lost by either</i>"<br /><br />No series can go on forever, but it's hard to say goodbye to old friends made through the course of 21 books, 21 mysteries solved together.<br /><br />"<i>There was no other way but straight forwards, to success or ruin.</i>"<br /><br />This was an exceptionally touching narrative. A beautifully crafted, emotional final farewell mystery for Brother Cadfael and his friends. I would have dearly loved to see the return of Brother Mark for one final sweet moment of inspiration and pride, but that was not to be. Brother Mark is safe with the bishop, and the civil war rumbles on too steadily for sentimentality. Dark news arrives for Cadfael from the south. "<i>Known to have been among those overpowered and disarmed, not known who holds him, or where. Has not been offered for ransom. Olivier de Bretagne.</i>" His only son is lost and imprisoned. Cadfael does, with little hesitation and wells of regret, what he must do. He breaks his monastic vows to go in search of his son. "<i>There was a sense of shock, grieved eyes turning silently upon a brother already almost renegade.</i>" He goes into a chaotic land, for once seen as the frail elderly being that he is, out of love.<br />"<i>'What is one man's fate beside the fate of the realm?'</i>"<br />He reaches the arch-bishops' conference at Coventry where king and empress are drawn together in a final effort at peace. "<i>And yet at last, neither side could ever win, neither side lose. And they would sicken at last of wasting their time, their lives, and their country.</i>" Cadfael's grief and selfless concern for his son is met with belligerence and conceit, a self-absorption that at once seems belittling and petty. Maud is embittered by the latest betrayal, little as she cares for the men involved, and yet still gets her way. "<i>'All the same, I must confess I should not be greatly grieved to see Brien de Soulis dead at my feet.'</i>"<br />With little to show for the conference but a murder, and murder of a man scheming to his last breath for his own betterment with another nobleman's seal hidden in his possessions "<i>'a man would be least likely to be parted with his seal. The thing carries his sanction, his honour, his reputation with it.'</i>", Cadfael follows the young traitor Philip FitzRobert down into the Cotswolds to his stone bastion of La Musarderie. There he confronts Lord Philip who has sent his own father's men to fight against his father, to hear Cadfael's plea on behalf of his own son Olivier. "<i>'We are born of the fathers we deserve, and they engender sons they deserve. We are our own penance and theirs.'</i>" These passages are hauntingly sad. Cadfael's patience never wavours against the young traitor's rage, and Cadfael's hope that Philip can be brought to forgive and reconcile is never shaken. This is a deeply emotional exchange worthy of high fantasy. <br />"<i>'None of us,' said Brother Cadfael ruefully, 'has ever done enough.'</i>"<br />He may be powerless against the might of Empress Maud's barons when they come for the traitor Philip in his whimsical and far-removed castle of La Musarderie. "<i>Worth it to take a man she hated, not worth it to redeem a man who had served her all too faithfully, and lost his liberty for her.</i>" But Brother Cadfael will unset this one young man's mind and set his son free. "<i>'All he saw was treason, and what you saw was a failure of understanding that was equally a betrayal.'</i>" With gentleness, patience, and hope, Cadfael achieves just that. With a never-ending compassion that does not pressure or judge, only forebears. And is eventually appreciated in return.<br /><br />"<i>Neither do I understand, thought Cadfael, but there is no need that I should. I trust, I respect, and I love.</i>"</span>
  <a data-text-id="5076778493530069148" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


