    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1949577553" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1949577553" />
    <a title="Robin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9348104-robin"><img alt="Robin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1336426974p2/9348104.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1949577553?book_show_action=true">Mar 22, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robin" href="/user/show/9348104-robin">Robin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1949577553" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13986590526921286846">Thoroughly enjoyed this book, the more so because of the poignancy of it being the final instalment in Cadfael&apos;s story. The narrative style took a little while to get into, but has a gentle lyric that really captures the mood of the unfolding story. In brief, Cadfael hears that he son has disappeared at the end of a battle and sets out to attend a peace conference where survivors of the battle might be able to help.<br/>The conference ends in murder, which leads to our sleuthing monk becoming trapped</span>
  <span id="freeText13986590526921286846" style="display:none">Thoroughly enjoyed this book, the more so because of the poignancy of it being the final instalment in Cadfael's story. The narrative style took a little while to get into, but has a gentle lyric that really captures the mood of the unfolding story. In brief, Cadfael hears that he son has disappeared at the end of a battle and sets out to attend a peace conference where survivors of the battle might be able to help.<br />The conference ends in murder, which leads to our sleuthing monk becoming trapped in a castle under siege before all is resolved. The unfolding story of political machinations, ambition, and forgiveness is gently and thoughtfully played out.Whilst not a Christian myself, the depth of the old monk's faith and its centrality to his life is beautifully evoked. The murder mystery is almost incidental to Cadfael's spiritual struggle to honour his conflicting duties to his own son and his loyalties to his monastic order.<br />As closure on the cycle of stories it sits alongside the Reichenbach Falls and Curtain, and recommended to lovers of medieval stories, religious fiction, and period murder mysteries.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13986590526921286846" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


