    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_115972413" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/115972413" />
    <a title="Kathryn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2224950-kathryn"><img alt="Kathryn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1428875161p2/2224950.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/115972413?book_show_action=true">Aug 09, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kathryn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kathryn" href="/user/show/2224950-kathryn">Kathryn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2224950-kathryn?shelf=2010">2010</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer115972413" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10754704152634791370">This is the last mystery novel of Brother Cadfael’s adventures (there is a book of three short stories, or novellas, which I shall read next), and I am sorry to bid Brother Cadfael adieu; but this particular mystery is a very good one, and deals with a crisis of competing values for our good Benedictine. I very much enjoyed this book, and hope to read it again (with the other nineteen books in the series) in another ten years or so.<br/><br/>It is the spring of 1145, and the maneuvering between the forces</span>
  <span id="freeText10754704152634791370" style="display:none">This is the last mystery novel of Brother Cadfael’s adventures (there is a book of three short stories, or novellas, which I shall read next), and I am sorry to bid Brother Cadfael adieu; but this particular mystery is a very good one, and deals with a crisis of competing values for our good Benedictine. I very much enjoyed this book, and hope to read it again (with the other nineteen books in the series) in another ten years or so.<br /><br />It is the spring of 1145, and the maneuvering between the forces loyal to King Stephen and those forces loyal to the Empress Maud continues, with a few new wrinkles. The castle and garrison of Faringdon, held by the Empress and under siege by the King, was by a secret compact engineered by its castellan, Brian de Soulis, delivered up to the King lock, stock, and barrel; those within who refused to switch their allegiance from the Empress to the King were disarmed, made prisoners, and distributed to the King’s officers as valuable ransom material. Additionally, Philip FitzRobert, son of Robert, 1st Earl of Gloucester (the half-brother of the Empress, and her right-hand man) gave over the castle and garrison of Cricklade to the King.<br /><br />So much is history. In this novel, a list of the prisoners taken at Faringdon has been made, with notations on who held each prisoner for ransom, and also noting which prisoners have been ransomed. Among the prisoners listed is Olivier de Bretagne, a valuable liegeman of Laurence d’Angers; it is known that he was taken at Faringdon as one who refused to change his allegiance from the Empress to the King, but it is not known who holds him, and he has not been offered for ransom. Brother Cadfael, upon learning this news, requests an interview with Abbot Radulfus, tells him that Olivier de Bretagne is his natural son (begat when Cadfael was on his way home from the Crusades, in Syria), and that Cadfael regards it as his bound right to search out the whereabouts of his son (who does not know who his father is) and restore him to full freedom. The Abbot gives Cadfael permission to go to Coventry, where a peace meeting between King Stephen and the Empress Maud is to be held, in company with Sheriff Hugh Beringar, to see if the whereabouts of his son may be discovered, but warns Cadfael that if he goes further he risks expulsion from the Benedictine Order.<br /><br />Hugh Beringar and Cadfael go to Coventry, where not only do they not uncover any clue as to the whereabouts of Oliver de Bretagne, but Brian de Soulis, who had betrayed Farington to the King, was found dead after Compline on the last night of the unsuccessful peace conference, with Yves Hugonin (last seen by Brother Cadfael in 1139, in the events related in <i>The Virgin in the Ice: The Sixth Chronicle of Brother Cadfael, of the Benedictine Abbey of St. Peter and St. Paul, at Shrewsbury</i> by Ellis Peters), who is now a liegeman to the Empress, bending over the body, his hand red with his blood.<br /><br />With the murder unsolved, but with popular suspicion (if not logic) pointing at Yves Hugonin as the murderer, Brother Cadfael sets his path away from Shrewsbury, and goes in search of information about his son. He has now put himself beyond the bounds set by his Abbot, and is therefore with every step towards his son’s freedom that much further from communion with his Benedictine brothers, and at very definite risk of being excommunicate for the rest of his life. The Benedictine vows are those of stability, conversion of manners, and obedience; and while Cadfael has stretched the bounds of his vows before, he has never yet stepped outside of them to this extent. As Cadfael seeks the freedom of his son, he realizes just how very much he needs to be a part of the Benedictine order, which has ordered his life for so many years.<br /><br />This book is a fitting conclusion to the series, and there is some indication that the author wrote this book as the end book of the series. There are those who long for Middle Earth, but I think a trip to the Abbey and a visit to Brother Cadfael’s herbrarium down at the end of the monastery garden would be more my style.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10754704152634791370" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


