        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer231324184" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5215508891215092758"><blockquote>We are born of the fathers we deserve, and they engender the sons they deserve. We are our own penance and theirs. The first murderous warfare in the world, we are told, was between two brothers, but the longest and the bitterest is between fathers and sons.</blockquote><br/>A magnificent ending to my favorite historical mystery series. Although the novel stands on its own, many of the characters were introduced earlier in the series. So it&apos;s more fun to read the books in order. I&apos;m grieving a bit to have come to</span>
  <span id="freeText5215508891215092758" style="display:none"><blockquote>We are born of the fathers we deserve, and they engender the sons they deserve. We are our own penance and theirs. The first murderous warfare in the world, we are told, was between two brothers, but the longest and the bitterest is between fathers and sons.</blockquote><br />A magnificent ending to my favorite historical mystery series. Although the novel stands on its own, many of the characters were introduced earlier in the series. So it's more fun to read the books in order. I'm grieving a bit to have come to the end of the series that has been my sure escape over the course of the many weeks it's taken to read them for a second time (after a period of 20 years or more since the first reading).<br /><br />Peters depicts the heart-wrenching anguish of Brother Cadfael as he breaks his monastic vow to look for his captive son, Olivier. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[And at long last Olivier learns that Cadfael is his father! <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> It's delightfully satisfying to meet up with young Yves Hugonin again, now six years older (19) than when we first met him in <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/847860.The_Virgin_in_the_Ice__Chronicles_of_Brother_Cadfael___6_" title="The Virgin in the Ice (Chronicles of Brother Cadfael, #6) by Ellis Peters" rel="nofollow noopener"> A Virgin in the Ice</a>. His impetuousness and eager loyalty to Olivier are wonderful foils to Cadfael's and Olivier's staid determination. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[Although the father/son relationship is primary for Cadfael and Olivier as well as Philip FitzRobert and Robert of Gloucester, there is also the compelling case of the Lady Jovetta, who murdered Brien de Solis to avenge the murder of her son, Geoffrey FitzClare. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> All in all, a very satisfying ending to a most excellent series. Highly recommended.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5215508891215092758" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

